doc.title: US Tariff Impact Tracker: Data Still Part of to Potential for Near-Term Import Weakness; Volatile Trends Continued
doc.source_uri: 2025-09-02/US Tariff Impact Tracker_ Data Still Pointing to Potential for Near-Term Import Weakness; Volatile Trends Continue_2025-09-02

passages.text: US Tariff Impact Tracker - Laden versus from China to USA dropped sequentially by \(10\%\) and were down \(19\%\) on a YoY basis. Data suggests 2H- August is shaping up to be up and down before turning more negative into the initial part of September based on Port of LA data - continuing the uncertain trends post the initial China surge. Full ramifications from the recent tariff- related implementations and magnitudes have yet to play out - but the next few weeks could continue to illustrate shipper reactions into the start of peak season ordering.
China freight flows (week ending Thursday, August 28) showed a sequential downtick in laden vessels from China to the US \((- 10\%)\) , as well as an accelerated YoY drop- off \((- 19\%)\) .

Port Optimizer sequentials indicate weakness again next week before reverting higher two weeks out; expected sequential imports into the Port of Los Angeles are set to decline by \(26\%\) TEUs (Sept 5), while the early read suggests a reversion is possible sequentially on a two- week out basis \((+30\%)\) .

Note that rail intermodal volumes in the West Coast declined by \(5\%\) YoY (following last week's decline of \(- 1\%\) ) after being positive in prior weeks - the recent positive growth trends likely reflected the load/unload- lag and freight moving out of warehouses, whereas more moderate intermodal growth could begin to reflect more muted import trends (should they persist as data suggests).
Ocean container rates were down \(1\%\) sequentially, and rates remain under considerable pressure on a YoY basis at \(- 75\%\) .

What We Disseminate Weekly: High frequency data to help assess the ongoing impact of tariffs on global supply chains and the accompanying ramifications on the flow of freight (e.g., expected ships leaving from China to USA). While we think our data set is representative, we do plan to periodically add new data series they become available.

It is important to recognize that weekly data can be volatile, with a fair bit of noise depending on timing - but we still think looking at the data collectively, and perhaps over a multi- week basis can be informative as to tariff- related trends.

In our view, as we exit the week, the key for peak season will be whether customers decide to remain in slow- down mode on activity/orders because of the uncertainty and not wanting to be caught with too much inventory or a changed situation on the tariff front. While our base case is that freight still enjoys peak season seasonality around the resilient consumer, it is conceivable that shippers/retailers could wait too long to place orders and arrange for shipping - if this were to materialize (we may need a few more weeks to ascertain this based on commentary from transports over earnings season), then peak season could yet underwhelm from a volume/revenue perspective. While this would pose some risk to 2H profit trajectory for our coverage group (another push to the right), it could also give rise to an interesting scenario as we move into 2026; namely, with inventories at retail not necessarily overburdened (see Exhibit 10 of our Monthly Mosaic), we could see the potential for a meaningful re- stock event (after a \(2+\) year freight recession largely focused on destocking) should the consumer remain resilient and spend during peak holiday shopping in 2025, and in conjunction with such factors as potential Fed cuts (GS economists predict three consecutive 25bps cuts beginning in September). Should we get a re- stock event in 2026, that would likely be quite favorable to overall freight flows and in turn incremental margins.

For the time being we note that the volatile nature and potential air pocket in 2H25 will likely impact all transports to the downside if consumer demand does not lift shipments post what is at least some near term pull- forward. We did however upgrade the truckers recently (see our upgrade note), as we think the likelihood of recession has lessened, and the consumer can stay relatively resilient (GS economists recently lowered their recession forecast by another \(5\%\) to \(30\%\) and increased its GDP outlook in the 4Q to \(1.3\%\) ).

In the near term, we expect freight forwarders EXPD and CHRW to benefit from 1) volatility as freight forwarders benefit in times of uncertainty, and 2) if the 90- day pause with China drives a meaningful surge in pull- forward, forwarders could capture enough volume and price to offset net revenue margin squeeze. Despite benefiting in the near term, we do note that the YoY comparisons for ocean rates will make it challenging, as we have seen ocean container rates up in recent weeks but struggling to be positive YoY.

Other beneficiaries could be the parcels (UPS and FDX - both Buy rated) with their fast cycle logistics and air freight as well as large global footprints that can help shippers shift supply chains. If demand for goods into the US spikes during this window, parcels could take advantage of the air demand via demand surcharges (weighed against the loss of the de minimis exemption) - as well as advantage if a peak season materializes in late 2025.

In a similar vein, if imports pulled in come into the West Coast primarily, this would likely benefit West Coast intermodal UNP and JBHT. On the other hand, 2H25 could become challenging if the pull- forward leads to a subseasonal fall peak in terms of freight flow.

We track weekly (and some daily) data that helps provide as real time as possible insights into trade volumes, demand and pricing. We note that much of this data is choppy in the near term and more than often shows trends developing over time as we receive more data, but also speaks to the volatility of trade flows. Therefore, we caution against drawing conclusions week to week but note that it can be helpful to see changes in the data week to week given the dynamic trade environment. Below, we track the high frequency data points that we believe are highly relevant to trade and US freight transportation.

Laden container vessels from China to the US were \(- 19\%\) YoY over the last week (8/22- 8/28) versus \(- 9\%\) YoY in the prior week (8/15- 8/21). The sequential vessel decrease of \(- 10\%\) in the most recent week is potentially revealing the slowing after an increase in activity post the US- China reprieve.

We estimate there could have been as much as \(\sim\) 3bn imported more in June YoY (\~53k more TEUs YoY x \\(57k), while May had a YoY decline of\) \sim 3bn\((- 55k less TEUs YoY x\) 57k). We estimate that July could have had as much as\) \sim 3bn\$ imported more YoY while August is tracking for \(\sim\) 1.2bn of YoY growth. Meanwhile, 1H- September is tracking for a decline of \(\sim\) 1.7B (given when is expected to arrive in terms of TEUs over the coming weeks).

We leverage a similar analysis from the Longshoreman strike last October (see our longshoreman impact note). According to the Bureau of Transportation Statistics, Ocean trade was about \(2.3tn\) in trade in 2022. The top 25 ports in the U.S. moved 44mn loaded TEUs in 2022, meaning that each loaded container (TEU) on average in 2022 had a value of \(\sim\) 52,000. Growing this by inflation of \(\sim 3\%\) for the last three years implied value per container or \(\sim\) 57,000. Multiplying the YoY change in TEUs with the value/TEU, we estimate the monthly imported value change YoY.

Exhibit 21: We estimate that June had a surge of trade following May's drop off; July/August tracked for continued growth albeit at a lower level versus June, while September is tracking for more of a drop- off - reflecting the current volatility of trade Implied Trade Value Change YoY Based on YoY TEU Change and Estimated Value/TEU
Source: Port Optimizer, US Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS), Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global cover, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
